Create a complete Blazor Web App for managing a veterinary clinic in /tmp/sv-0927182a7dc246c18563cce6a1d4f2e0. The app must use Interactive Server render mode globally (all pages involve data entry and real-time interactions, accessed from local network workstations).

## Architecture Decisions
- **Blazor Web App** with **Interactive Server** render mode set globally
- **ASP.NET Core Identity** for staff authentication (individual accounts, cookie auth)
- **Entity Framework Core with SQLite** for data storage
- **Bootstrap 5** for UI (included by default)

## Step-by-step instructions

### 1. Scaffold the project

```bash
cd /tmp/sv-0927182a7dc246c18563cce6a1d4f2e0
dotnet new blazor -n VetClinic --interactivity Server --auth Individual --all-interactive
```

This creates a solution with VetClinic and VetClinic.Client projects. Since we're using Server interactivity globally, we'll put everything in the main VetClinic project.

### 2. Data Model

Create the following entity classes in `VetClinic/Models/`:

**Owner.cs**
```csharp
namespace VetClinic.Models;

public class Owner
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string FirstName { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string LastName { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Phone { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Email { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public List<Pet> Pets { get; set; } = new();
}
```

**Pet.cs**
```csharp
namespace VetClinic.Models;

public class Pet
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
